  <div class="page-container">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>{meta.title}</h1>
      <p>{meta.description}</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>How to Play Truth or Dare</h2>
      <p>Truth or Dare is a classic party game that requires no equipment, just a group of willing participants. The premise is simple: players take turns asking each other "Truth or Dare?".</p>

      <h3>Rules Variations</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Classic:</strong> Take turns in a circle. You must answer truthfully or perform the dare.</li>
        <li><strong>Double Dare:</strong> If you refuse a dare, you can be double-dared, meaning the dare becomes harder, but you can't back out!</li>
        <li><strong>Pick Your Poison:</strong> Write truths and dares on slips of paper and draw from two separate bowls.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Drinking Game Version (Play Responsibly!)</h3>
      <p><em>Disclaimer: Must be of legal drinking age. Please drink responsibly and know your limits.</em></p>
      <p>In the drinking version, if a player refuses to answer a truth or complete a dare, they must take a predetermined number of sips. You can also implement a "group cheers" whenever a particularly spicy truth is revealed.</p>

      <h3>Virtual / Zoom Adaptations</h3>
      <p>Playing over video calls is easy! Use the random generator or read questions from this guide. Dares can include showing the last photo on your phone, doing jumping jacks on camera, or sending a message to a random contact while sharing your screen.</p>

      <h3>Spin the Bottle Integration</h3>
      <p>Combine two classics! Sit in a circle and spin a bottle. Whoever the bottle points to must choose Truth or Dare, and the person who spun the bottle gets to ask the question or assign the dare.</p>

      <h3>Custom Dare Ideas</h3>
      <p>Want to make your own dares? Keep them relevant to your environment. At a sleepover? Dare someone to go outside in their pajamas. At a restaurant? Dare someone to ask the waiter a funny question.</p>

      <h3>How to Set Boundaries</h3>
      <p>It's crucial that everyone feels safe. Before playing, establish "off-limits" topics or actions. It's okay to have a "pass" rule where each player gets one free pass without penalty.</p>

      <h3>Truth or Dare History</h3>
      <p>Did you know Truth or Dare has been played for centuries? A variation called "Questions and Commands" was popular in the 1700s, where players were given a command to follow or a question they had to answer truthfully.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="games-list">
